At least six times in the last two years, Warren has asked senior military leaders to acknowledge the threat posed by climate change.
Since the Obama administration, military leaders have readily acknowledged the dangers of rising seas, wildfires, droughts, and extreme weather—all conditions that are exacerbated by climate change.
“Tying things to climate change could invite a scrutiny that was undesired,” Rear Adm. Jonathan White, who led the Navy’s climate change task force from 2012 to 2015, told Mother Jones in December.
The Marines requested more than $3 billion to rebuild Camp Lejeune while the Air Force has spent hundreds of millions of dollars to renovate Tyndall Air Force Base.
In November 2017, the Government Accountability Office made six recommendations to the Pentagon regarding the impact of climate change on overseas installations.